Energy is fundamentally critical and unbelievably complex. Last year, Julia=
 DeWahl and I spent a whole 10-episode season [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/1a841e42-4609-44ca-9373-509fb0676407?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] digging into how America can start produc=
ing nuclear energy again. But nuclear is just one generation technology, an=
d generation (or production) is just one of the three legs of the electrici=
ty stool alongside delivery and consumption.=C2=A0
For the energy transition to succeed, and for the world to consume multiple=
s more energy than we do today, all three legs need to improve.=C2=A0
On the production side, we need more and cheaper nuclear, solar, wind, geot=
hermal, synthetic fuels, and other carbon-free sources of energy.=C2=A0
On the consumption side, we need to electrify everything we can economicall=
y electrify =E2=80=93 from cars to heat pumps to appliances.=C2=A0
The good news is: both are happening!=C2=A0
Solar is getting unbelievably cheap, electric vehicle (EV) penetration cont=
inues to rise, and scores of incredibly smart people are working to produce=
 electricity more cheaply and consume that cheap electricity in more ways.=
=C2=A0
The bad news is: both of those things actually make the delivery problem wo=
rse!=C2=A0
Delivery involves moving electrons from where they=E2=80=99re produced to w=
here they=E2=80=99re consumed, like from a coal plant or solar farm to a ho=
me or business. There=E2=80=99s transmission =E2=80=93 moving electrons ove=
r long distances from power plants to substations using high-voltage lines =
=E2=80=93 and distribution =E2=80=93 moving electrons from the substation t=
o homes and businesses over the regular low-voltage power lines you=E2=80=
=99re used to seeing.=C2=A0
This whole electricity delivery system is known as =E2=80=9Cthe grid.=E2=80=
=9D And the grid is a bit of a mess.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s buckling due to four factors Construction Physics=E2=80=99 Bri=
an Potter describes [ https://substack.com/redirect/4cde3685-1904-4d69-b741=
-f90c7936fb27?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] as, =E2=80=9Cincreasing use of variable sources of electricity, dec=
reasing grid reliability, increasing delay in building electrical infrastru=
cture, and increasing demand for electricity.=E2=80=9D
The bookend threats =E2=80=93 increasing use of variable sources of electri=
city and increasing demand for electricity =E2=80=93 present a particularly=
 paradoxical problem. The more progress we make in wind, solar, EVs, and el=
ectric stoves, the more unstable the grid gets.=C2=A0
The power supply is increasingly variable and unreliable. The demand for po=
wer is growing and increasingly volatile. Just as everyone gets home, plugs=
 in their Tesla, and turns on all of their shiny electric stuff, the sun se=
ts!=C2=A0=C2=A0
With more demand for electricity, delivery gets more expensive, because tra=
nsmission lines need to be sized for peak load. One solution is just to add=
 more transmission capacity, but fixing the grid itself by modernizing or a=
dding transmission is, like any big project in America, getting harder, slo=
wer, and more expensive to do.=C2=A0
This is the bottleneck standing between us and our clean, abundant energy f=
uture, and it=E2=80=99s the piece of the energy puzzle that has attracted t=
he least entrepreneurial attention.=C2=A0
So it=E2=80=99s the challenge that Base Power Company plans to solve.=C2=A0
Base is building =E2=80=9Cthe Modern Power Company of the Electric Era.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s starting by deploying connected batteries across the grid in p=
laces where interconnect already exists and where the demand happens: in pe=
oples=E2=80=99 homes, beginning with Texas.=C2=A0
Batteries can fix us. They solve electricity=E2=80=99s big challenge: match=
ing electricity production and consumption. Batteries can store electricity=
 on the cheap when the sun shines and the wind blows and discharge it whene=
ver people want to turn on their appliances, reducing strain on the grid.=
=C2=A0
And batteries are booming. Installed storage capacity tripled from 2020 to =
2021, then doubled in both 2022 and 2023. The Energy Information Agency pre=
dicts capacity will grow another 80% this year. That=E2=80=99s both a conse=
quence and a cause of the fact that batteries are getting cheaper. Prices h=
ave fallen 82% over the past decade, and with more battery production, pric=
es continue to fall.=C2=A0
Battery installation isn=E2=80=99t progressing as quickly as it could, howe=
ver, thanks in part to the long interconnect queues =E2=80=93 waiting to ge=
t connected to the grid =E2=80=93 that are plaguing energy projects of all =
sorts. Most of the battery storage capacity in the US is concentrated in ce=
ntralized grid-scale battery farms, which have to wait for interconnection.=
=C2=A0
But what if you go to where interconnection is freely available =E2=80=93 c=
ustomers=E2=80=99 homes? Residential batteries are actually ideal for a few=
 reasons.=C2=A0
Justin told me to imagine the grid as a single line from the solar farm to =
the home and asked: =E2=80=9CWhere on the line do you put the battery?=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
If you put it next to the solar farm, you go a long way towards solving the=
 supply volatility problem.=C2=A0
The grid views a battery farm like a more flexible nuclear plant =E2=80=93 =
reliable supply that can be ramped up or down as needed. But you still need=
 transmission and distribution lines between the solar farm and the house t=
o support the maximum load that the home could pull, because people will st=
ill turn on their AC and charge their EVs when they get home.=C2=A0
But if you slide the battery all the way over to the right and put it next =
to the home, you solve the supply volatility problem and the demand volatil=
ity problem.=C2=A0
Call that the Electric Slide.
From the perspective of the grid, it looks like the home is consistently de=
manding about one-quarter of its peak load. The battery charges when demand=
, and therefore price, is low, and discharges into the home when demand, an=
d therefore price, is high. It smooths out the demand curve, which means le=
ss load on transmission lines.=C2=A0
As the demand for electricity is expected to double or triple by 2050, solv=
ing the demand volatility is crucial. If you want to really solve the grid =
bottleneck, you need residential batteries.=C2=A0
So why is the vast majority of the battery installation grid-scale (i.e. ne=
