What Base is Building
The simplest way to describe Base=E2=80=99s business is that it=E2=80=99s b=
uilding a large portfolio of connected batteries with short paybacks and hi=
gh cash on cash returns. That simplicity masks a whole lot of complexity.=
=C2=A0
Base Power Company is a Retail Electric Provider (REP) in Texas. It buys po=
wer from the grid and sells it to customers.=C2=A0
It installs a large battery =E2=80=93 20kWh versus 13.5 kWh for a Tesla Pow=
erwall, increasing to 30kWh in future models =E2=80=93 in each customer=E2=
=80=99s home. The size is designed to max out a home=E2=80=99s standard 240=
 volt 200 amp electrical capacity, which means it can provide whole home ba=
ckup while supporting the grid. It also decreases install times by 50-75% b=
y eliminating the need to install a critical loads panel, which you=E2=80=
=99d need for a smaller battery that can=E2=80=99t power the whole home. Wi=
th larger batteries, the battery becomes the home=E2=80=99s single interfac=
e with the grid.=C2=A0
Base assembles and will soon manufacture battery packs itself, but it doesn=
=E2=80=99t make battery cells. A cell is the basic unit of a battery [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/eca877c1-3be6-4e2e-9896-10dfb3d75422?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 the thin=
g with the anode, cathode, and electrolyte that generates electricity throu=
gh chemical reactions. A pack consists of multiple battery cells, the casin=
g, the Battery Management System, cooling system, and connectors. It distri=
butes and manages the power generated by the individual cells. Base believe=
s that cells will be commoditized, and that pack assembly allows it to bene=
fit from that commoditization and potentially integrate new cell types as b=
etter chemistries emerge.=C2=A0
It also manages installations itself, which it views as tightly coupled wit=
h pack assembly. It calls the whole process the Deployment Factory. Packs n=
eed to be manufactured in such a way that they=E2=80=99re easy to install. =
Modular design with no forklifts or cranes required. Connectors instead of =
wires that need to be cut and crimped. It=E2=80=99s not the way you=E2=80=
=99d design a specific battery for optimal performance, but how you=E2=80=
=99d design the whole system for optimal performance.=C2=A0
Base owns the battery, and customers only pay the install cost versus the n=
early $20k total cost of buying a system with equivalent power. Base believ=
es that this model is a big unlock in driving consumer adoption. Instead of=
 asking customers to take on a decade-plus payback, Base takes it (and the =
upside) on itself.=C2=A0
Unlike customers, which can finance individual batteries at high rates, Bas=
e can build a portfolio of batteries and get cheaper asset-backed loans at =
the portfolio level. Unlike battery farms, it doesn=E2=80=99t sign offtake =
agreements but trades in volatile power markets, which means it can=E2=80=
=99t lever up as much as battery farms can. But because it manufactures its=
 own batteries, it doesn=E2=80=99t need to pay the margins to Tesla that ba=
ttery farms do, either.=C2=A0 That said, between loans and the 30% IRA tax =
credits, Base expects it will be able to spend less equity on each battery =
and generate higher yields than it could without debt, as long as it makes =
money on the batteries.=C2=A0
To that end, because Base is an REP, it can make money by trading electrici=
ty in wholesale markets, which it believes will lower its paybacks and incr=
ease its yields. It buys power from the grid when prices are low and it sel=
ls power back to the grid when prices are high. It can do this because the =
battery can store the electrons it acquires cheaply and discharge them when=
ever they=E2=80=99re needed. As the team wrote in one memo, =E2=80=9CYour h=
ome or office should run on 4am power, not 6pm power.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Base is starting in Texas for a number of reasons. The first is that the cu=
stomer pain is particularly acute in Texas, where there are 6x more outages=
 than there were a decade ago.
Relatedly, thanks to a confluence of factors we=E2=80=99ll discuss, power p=
rices in Texas are particularly volatile and getting more volatile as the s=
tate continues to lead the way in renewable generation installs. Since Base=
 can buy low and sell high, the larger the gap between high and low, the mo=
re money it can make.=C2=A0
In order for all of this to work, Base is building sensors and software to =
aggregate demand signals from its network of connected batteries and charge=
 and discharge electricity based on those signals. A giant fleet of softwar=
e-controlled energy storage systems that Base can control should give them =
an edge in power trading, improve their customers=E2=80=99 reliability, and=
 help improve the performance of the grid overall.=C2=A0
If Base is successful in power trading, it can improve its paybacks, increa=
se its yields, and give customers savings on their electricity bills, which=
 would allow the company to expand its battery fleet more quickly. A larger=
 battery fleet means more signals, more profit, and a greater ability to im=
pact the grid.=C2=A0
Ultimately, with a large enough fleet, Base imagines it could backwards int=
egrate into power generation and build a modern utility with some clean she=
et advantages. If you were starting a utility today, you wouldn=E2=80=99t b=
uild coal or gas generators; you=E2=80=99d build nuclear, solar, and wind. =
But many who have tried to compete directly with utilities on that premise =
have failed. Starting by owning demand, though, could give Base a cost of c=
apital advantage: they=E2=80=99d already have the buyer for the power they =
generate.=C2=A0
That, the company believes, is how you build the Modern Power Company of th=
e Electric Era.=C2=A0
Simple, right?=C2=A0
Now that we=E2=80=99ve covered the what, painted a picture of how all the p=
ieces fit together, we can dig deeper into the series of why=E2=80=99s that=
 led there.=C2=A0
Why is the grid crumbling? Why batteries? Why vertically integrate? Why a R=
etail Electric Provider? Why distributed? Why Texas?
We=E2=80=99ll start with the macro situation =E2=80=93 with the grid and ba=
tteries =E2=80=93 before getting into the micro of the decisions that Base =
is making to fix the situation and build a valuable business.=C2=A0
Then, once we have that, we can imagine how Base might expand from the init=
ial market into a modern high-margin utility that fixes the grid and lets A=
mericans use all the solar, nuclear, and wind we need to power all the EVs,=
 AC, and electric appliances we want.=C2=A0
Why the Grid is Crumbling
If your goal is to solve a really big challenge, the electric grid is a wor=
thy foe.=C2=A0
The grid has been called the largest and most complex machine in the world,=
 and for good reason. As Anna-Sofia Lesiv wrote in her excellent overview o=
f the grid [ https://substack.com/redirect/b61a13a1-4c3d-46c6-985c-cb762c5e=
5693?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
in the US alone, it connects over 11,900 power plants, each a complex machi=
ne in its own right, over more than 160,000 miles of high-voltage power lin=
es, and millions more miles of low-voltage distribution lines.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Maybe the best way to understand the grid is from the perspective of the po=
wer that flows through it. The journey begins at a generation facility =E2=
=80=93 a nuclear plant or solar farm, for example =E2=80=93 where various f=
orms of energy are converted into electrical energy. Electricity is produce=
d at low voltages, gets stepped up via transformers to high voltages, and t=
ravels from the plant through high-voltage transmission lines designed to c=
arry it hundreds or thousands of miles. As it approaches its final destinat=
ion, the power goes through a substation, where transformers step it down t=
o lower voltages, before speeding on to low-voltage distribution lines. Onc=
e it hits your neighborhood, the power=E2=80=99s voltage is stepped down on=
ce more via a transformer before the power travels down one last wire to yo=
ur home=E2=80=99s service panel (which contains the circuit breaker you nee=
d to flick when the power goes out), where it=E2=80=99s distributed to vari=
ous circuits in your home.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The absolutely incredible thing about this whole system is just how fast ev=
erything happens. When you turn on your air conditioning, it uses power tha=
t was generated hundreds of miles away about one second ago. As Casey Handm=
er writes [ https://substack.com/redirect/9cf0c5ed-2e41-4abb-8997-b4b72b355=
979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
=E2=80=9CTransmission moves power through space (technically null space, at=
 the speed of light).=E2=80=9D
This is both a miracle and a curse. a16z=E2=80=99s Ryan McEntush explains t=
his double-edged sword [ https://substack.com/redirect/0c372d86-ee79-466f-a=
7ad-92ab218d441d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CAt all times, electricity generated must match electri=
city demand, or =E2=80=98load=E2=80=99; this is what people mean when they =
say =E2=80=98balance the grid.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Making matters more challenging, the grid has to be sized for peak load: fo=
r that really hot day every decade when everyone turns their AC all the way=
 up all at once. There needs to be enough generation capacity to produce th=
e load and enough transmission capacity to move it, even if it=E2=80=99s ve=
ry infrequently used.=C2=A0
In an interview for Age of Miracles, Meredith Angwin [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/67d920da-5242-4bdf-a570-f16826fe2504?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the =E2=80=9CGrandmother of the G=
rid,=E2=80=9D told us that utilities have to pay certain generation facilit=
ies to just not shut down, even if they=E2=80=99re not producing power, jus=
t in case they=E2=80=99re needed. These =E2=80=9Ccapacity payments=E2=80=9D=
 make everyone=E2=80=99s electric bill higher. They=E2=80=99re an inelegant=
 financial band-aid for a problem that can now be solved with technology.=
=C2=A0
Balancing the grid has always been a challenge, one often solved by picking=
 up the phone and frantically calling generation facilities to turn product=
ion on or off ASAP, or by dumping perfectly good electricity with nowhere t=
o go. Occasionally, when things go really wrong, there are blackouts, which=
 cause everything from inconvenience to economic interruption to death.=C2=
=A0
But largely, for most of its life, the grid worked. Baseload power plants r=
un consistently to meet the consistent demand for electricity, and more exp=
ensive peaker plants are dispatched as needed to meet higher periods of dem=
and. Supply was dispatchable as-needed, and demand, while weather-dependent=
, was predictable.=C2=A0
Back in college, I interned on an energy trading desk, and every morning, t=
he first thing I did was check the weather: if it was going to be really ho=
t, prices would spike as more expensive peaker plants came online. But if I=
, as a dumb intern, knew that, it was a very predictable and largely non-th=
reatening spike.=C2=A0
With the rise of renewables and the electrification of everything, that=E2=
=80=99s changed. =E2=80=9CFor most of its history, electric power generatio=
n worked like any other machine - it was turned on when it was needed, and =
turned off when it wasn=E2=80=99t,=E2=80=9D Brian Potter wrote, =E2=80=9CBu=
t the predictability of power generation is slowly going out the window.=E2=
=80=9D
Instead of (largely) predictable supply serving (largely) predictable deman=
d, we increasingly have volatile supply meeting volatile (and growing) dema=
nd.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhen you have a system with volatility on one end and volatility o=
n the other,=E2=80=9D Jared explained to me, =E2=80=9Cthe basic engineering=
 principle is: don=E2=80=99t couple them. Don=E2=80=99t force yourself to c=
ontrol one with respect to the other.=E2=80=9D But that=E2=80=99s how we op=
erate the grid today. Most of the time, it=E2=80=99s fine, but more and mor=
e frequently, it=E2=80=99s not.=C2=A0
As Brian Potter points out in The Grid, Part IV [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/4cde3685-1904-4d69-b741-f90c7936fb27?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the introduction of variable sources o=
f electricity, like solar=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
=E2=80=A6 coupled with a National Renewable Energy Laboratory-predicted tri=
pling of electricity demand by 2050=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
=E2=80=A6 means that =E2=80=9Cthe grid faces several challenges that threat=
en its ability to distribute electric power.=E2=80=9D
Already, outages are increasing dramatically.=C2=A0
Potter cites a number of factors for decreasing reliability, chief among th=
em the rise in extreme weather conditions. Extreme weather can take down di=
stribution lines, shut down electricity generation, and spike demand, somet=
imes all at once!=C2=A0
And it=E2=80=99s only going to get worse. As we rip out more coal plants, f=
ail to build nuclear, and install more solar and wind, supply will continue=
 to get more volatile. As we electrify our cars, heating, and appliances, d=
emand will continue to get more volatile. But we need to do both of those t=
hings in order to avoid a climate disaster.=C2=A0
So what do you do?=C2=A0
One obvious solution which we spent a whole season of Age of Miracles [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/5632a086-9c8a-41ee-9b3c-010e54d6873f?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] covering is to bu=
ild more nuclear. Nuclear is clean, firm, baseload power. It=E2=80=99s pred=
ictable. We should absolutely, 100% do that, and a host of startups are wor=
king to make it possible. But nuclear, as implemented in America at least, =
is slow to turn on and off. It can=E2=80=99t respond to spikes in demand. I=
t helps solve half the issue.=C2=A0
Another obvious solution is just to build more transmission and distributio=
n. But if you=E2=80=99ve been reading Not Boring, you know how incredibly d=
ifficult it is to build big things in America. Aside from nuclear, transmis=
sion might be the most difficult thing for us to build.=C2=A0
As Ryan McEntush covers [ https://substack.com/redirect/0c372d86-ee79-466f-=
a7ad-92ab218d441d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], electrical infrastructure is slow and expensive to replace and=
 build due to a witches=E2=80=99 brew of issues, ranging from the standard =
NEPA reviews to an overwhelming deluge of applications to build to run-of-t=
he-mill supply chain issues for transformers and electrical steel. The aver=
age overhead transmission line takes more than a decade to build, seven yea=
rs of which is spent in planning and permitting!=C2=A0
So again, what do you do?=C2=A0
While we=E2=80=99ll still need to build and replace transmission and distri=
bution, the most pressing thing that we can do is to smooth supply and dema=
nd across time to give the grid a break.=C2=A0
Why Batteries?=C2=A0
To fix the grid, just add batteries.=C2=A0
Smoothing electricity supply and demand over time is what batteries were bo=
rn to do. In the bluntly titled Grid Storage: Why Batteries Will Win [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/9cf0c5ed-2e41-4abb-8997-b4b72b355979?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Casey Handmer wro=
te:=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s the key insight. Batteries and transmission are in direct co=
mpetition. Both enable electricity arbitrage =E2=80=93 the profitable repri=
cing of a resource by matching different levels of supply and demand. Trans=
mission moves power through space (technically null space, at the speed of =
light) and batteries move power through time.
What follows from that key insight is a thorough and data-driven demolition=
 of the idea that adding more grid is the right way to fix the grid. A few =
highlights:=C2=A0
Adding 12 hours of storage to the entire US grid would not happen overnight=
, but on current trends would cost around $500b and pay for itself within a=
 few years. This is a shorter timescale than the required manufacturing ram=
p, meaning it could be entirely privately funded. By contrast, upgrading th=
e US transmission grid could cost $7t over 20 years [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/3dfddd49-1d84-40c7-bf45-10fc14537813?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
In all cases, we see a grid without storage is useless=E2=80=A6 Conversely,=
 we see relatively small quantities of overall storage dramatically decreas=
e the amount of generation overbuild needed. Over a wide range of wind/sola=
r mix and battery installation, we can hit 99.99% reliability (significantl=
y better than the pre-renewable grid) with < 10x nameplate overbuild. This =
is how the grid will look in the future.
Adding marginal batteries until demand saturates will generate enormous pro=
fit and value growth. Adding additional grid is just stranding assets.
Casey calls his view =E2=80=9Cunconventional, even controversial,=E2=80=9D =
and arguably his =E2=80=9Cspiciest hot take on the future of energy,=E2=80=
=9D but the more I=E2=80=99ve dug in, the more I agree with him.=C2=A0
Batteries aren=E2=80=99t a generation technology =E2=80=93 we can=E2=80=99t=
 produce more energy with batteries =E2=80=93 but they supercharge other fo=
rms of clean generation.=C2=A0
As we=E2=80=99ve discussed, batteries are a great complement to variable ge=
neration sources like solar and wind. Solar and wind produce power whenever=
 the sun shines and the wind blows, but people=E2=80=99s energy consumption=
 doesn=E2=80=99t match the weather=E2=80=99s whims. Batteries can store pow=
er generated whenever it=E2=80=99s generated, and dispatch it whenever it=
=E2=80=99s needed.=C2=A0
But batteries are also a great complement to nuclear power. As Base wrote i=
n a recent memo, =E2=80=9CNuclear has high upfront costs but very low opera=
ting costs. Load side storage helps match the consistent output of nuclear =
to variable load and increases the economic value of energy generated from =
nuclear.=E2=80=9D Batteries make nuclear dispatchable.
In fact, they point out, batteries are a great complement to any high capex=
, low opex source of energy. If a plant is expensive to build but produces =
cheap energy thereafter, batteries can soak up all of the cheap output to b=
e dispatched when demand calls. That allows power generation owners to amor=
tize their capex over more demand, or to pay back their capex more quickly.=
 Batteries make renewable energy =E2=80=93 definitionally low opex =E2=80=
=93 more competitive with fossil fuel plants, which are less expensive to b=
uild but must consistently feed fuel into the system.=C2=A0
Batteries are also great for the grid.=C2=A0
The grid is designed to carry the peak load customers are expected to deman=
d. If demand gets spikier, grid operators need to add more transmission cap=
acity to meet peak loads, even if most of that capacity sits unused most of=
 the time.=C2=A0
Load factor is the ratio of average power demand to peak power demand over =
a given period. A low load factor means wasted resources. As an example, Te=
xas=E2=80=99 grid is sized for 85 GW based on last summer=E2=80=99s peak. C=
urrently, it=E2=80=99s running at a load of 48.8 GW [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/159e4332-e50b-42ed-81fb-42b16a9ea7b4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. That=E2=80=99s a load factor of 57=
%.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Maximizing load factor means the grid can operate more efficiently. Stabili=
zing load factor helps to minimize fluctuations in demand, which can reduce=
 strain on the grid and improve its overall reliability.=C2=A0
Batteries can help maximize and stabilize load factor by charging when dema=
nd is low, thereby increasing trough demand, and discharging when demand is=
 high, thereby lowering peak demand.=C2=A0
In the short term, batteries can stabilize load factor on the existing grid=
, even in the face of more variable renewable energy and electrification. O=
ver the long term, as electrification drives more demand for power, batteri=
es can help maximize load factor and avoid expensive buildout.=C2=A0
Which begs the question: if batteries are so miraculous, though, why aren=
=E2=80=99t they everywhere?=C2=A0
First off, give them time. Battery capacity has been growing rapidly. Betwe=
en 2021 and 2023, installed capacity tripled from 5 gigawatts (GW) to 15 GW=
=2E The EIA expects capacity to double=20=
again this year to 30 GW and grow by a=
nother third the following to over 40 GW.=C2=A0
The biggest issue with batteries has been their cost. Beautifully, however,=
 as we produce more of them, they get cheaper. They=E2=80=99re riding a lea=
rning curve. With every doubling of cumulative capacity, the price per kilo=
watt hour declines by 18.9%.=C2=A0
Last year, batteries hit a record low price [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/627d8a03-6a49-4d05-8d9e-89efb96d165f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of $139/kWh, down from $780/kWh in real 202=
3 dollars a decade earlier.=C2=A0
These were the trends that got Zach so excited about batteries in the first=
 place. Batteries were growing more quickly, and getting cheaper, than most=
 people realized.=C2=A0
That was the opportunity.=C2=A0
Why Vertically Integrate?
But what was the best way to capture the opportunity? Should you make cells=
? Manufacture packs? Install batteries that other people make to power elec=
trification? Sell battery management system software that rides on batterie=
s people have installed to build a virtual power plant? Do any or all of th=
ese things nationwide, or in a specific geography?=C2=A0
The answer isn=E2=80=99t straightforward. There are nice businesses to be b=
uilt in each. But to really solve the problem, and build the biggest busine=
ss, the team decided that it would have to vertically integrate and do a li=
ttle bit of all of it.=C2=A0
So which pieces do you integrate? What do you do yourself and what do you b=
uy off-the-shelf? Where do you start?=C2=A0
Building a great product is hard, but it=E2=80=99s relatively straightforwa=
