But Base=E2=80=99s goal isn=E2=80=99t to build the world=E2=80=99s best REP=
=2E It wants to build one of the cou=
ntry=E2=80=99s largest and most profitabl=
e battery storage portfolios. The REP is a channel to get as many batteries=
 as possible distributed across the state of Texas, to start, as quickly an=
d cheaply as possible.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The core business is using those batteries to trade energy and provide anci=
llary services to the grid.=C2=A0
Why is distributed better for power trading and ancillary services?=C2=A0
Base plans to make money by soaking up energy when it=E2=80=99s cheap and d=
ischarging it when it=E2=80=99s expensive. If they do it right, it=E2=80=99=
s a win-win: good for the business, and good for the grid.=C2=A0
There are two main ways it can make money this way: power trading and grid =
ancillary services.=C2=A0
Power trading is straightforward: buy low, sell high.=C2=A0
Because Base is an REP, it can buy electricity at off-peak times when price=
s are low, and sell it back to both customers and the grid when prices are =
high. Power can be purchased in real-time or day-ahead markets, and owning =
storage capacity means that Base can purchase in the more stable day-ahead =
markets and sell into more volatile real-time markets (or soak up more powe=
r real-time when prices are unexpectedly low). If Base can consistently cha=
rge when prices are low and discharge when they=E2=80=99re high, it can mak=
e money.=C2=A0
Now that Base has its first REP customers, it=E2=80=99s kicked off trading.=
 The image below shows that it sold power it had stored =E2=80=93 some to c=
ustomers, some back to the grid. They=E2=80=99re small numbers, but Base po=
wer trading is officially in business.=C2=A0
Grid ancillary services are things that the grid pays market participants t=
o do in order to stabilize the grid. They include frequency regulation (cha=
rging or discharging on-demand to balance drops or spikes in grid frequency=
), voltage support (injecting or absorbing the power needed to support the =
magnetic and electric fields in transformers, electric motors, and relays),=
 reserves (standing ready to inject power into the grid in the case of gene=
ration shortfalls), demand response (getting paid to lower usage), and ramp=
 support and load following (quickly ramping up or down to match variabilit=
y in renewable energy generation). The grid pays companies for providing th=
ese services, either directly through mechanisms like capacity payments or =
indirectly through markets.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve heard of the =E2=80=9Cduck curve,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s t=
he phenomenon where net demand for energy from the traditional grid is low =
during the day when solar power is firing, and then ramps quickly when the =
sun sets. Even though it=E2=80=99s predictable, it=E2=80=99s tricky to get =
all of the traditional generating capacity fired up to meet such a sharp in=
crease in demand. Batteries can help, as Patrick Collison points out, and t=
he grid will pay battery operators for that capability.=C2=A0
Base will make money in both ways: through trading and ancillary services. =
But so do battery farms, and battery farms have a much simpler model.=C2=A0
Building out a distributed network of batteries is a hard and potentially e=
xpensive thing to do. You need to build the batteries, acquire customers on=
e-at-a-time, and install batteries, then you need to manage those batteries=
, buy electricity from generators, and bill customers and handle their cust=
omer service inquiries.=C2=A0
Considering all that, it=E2=80=99s understandable that most of the big play=
ers have built centralized battery farms. If they make money by buying a bu=
nch of batteries on leverage and paying them back by trading power and prov=
