But putting smart batteries next to load has advantages if you=E2=80=99re a=
ble to overcome the challenges.=C2=A0
Earlier, we discussed why residential batteries are better for the grid. Pu=
tting them next to the home solves demand and supply volatility. Importantl=
y, residential batteries lower congestion on the grid at peak times, loweri=
ng overall power costs.=C2=A0
That California batteries versus duck curve chart that Patrick Collison twe=
eted is great, but as Ryan McEntush pointed out in response, transmission p=
rices spike as all of those batteries discharge power onto transmission lin=
es at once, making power even more expensive.=C2=A0
The price spike isn=E2=80=99t the batteries=E2=80=99 fault. Something was g=
oing to need to put a lot of power on the grid quickly. But the problem rem=
ains: the transmission costs are too damn high!=C2=A0=C2=A0
There used to be a bit on the Reply All podcast called Yes Yes No, where on=
e co-host would read a random tweet and the other would try to figure out w=
hat it meant. Now that we=E2=80=99re nearly 10,000 words in, we can play a =
little Yes Yes No of our own:=C2=A0
Casey says that we need less than one order of magnitude more batteries to =
support California=E2=80=99s heavily-renewable grid. The Dude replies that =
we still have a transmission problem, because batteries are centralized and=
 discharge into an overloaded grid at the same time. Casey replies that suf=
ficient batteries solve this problem. And The Dude tells them that batterie=
s don=E2=80=99t solve the problem unless you put them where the demand is, =
which he says is inefficient!=C2=A0
Putting batteries on premise is what Base is doing. It=E2=80=99s how you so=
lve the grid. In the last two sections, we talked about how Base plans to h=
andle the inefficiency by manufacturing battery packs, getting really good =
at install, and building a modern REP that can acquire customers efficientl=
y. Solve the inefficiency, solve the grid.=C2=A0
But while the Base team wants to solve a really big challenge, they=E2=80=
=99re not doing this altruistically. They want to solve a big challenge by =
building a big business.=C2=A0
It turns out, if you can overcome the inefficiencies, building a distribute=
d storage portfolio also has advantages for both trading and ancillary serv=
ices.=C2=A0
It starts with better data. Because Base=E2=80=99s battery is the home=E2=
=80=99s interface with the grid, it knows what=E2=80=99s happening on its c=
ustomers=E2=80=99 circuits in real-time. Fluctuations in demand are mainly =
a function of residential HVAC, and Base knows when people are turning on t=
heir air conditioners before anyone else in the market. They know what=E2=
=80=99s happening in real-time because they have a computer managing demand=
 on every battery. Other market participants get data on a 5-minute delay. =
With more batteries, that should give them an increasingly unfair advantage=
=2E
Jared told me that since most of the grid was built over 50 years ago, it d=
oesn=E2=80=99t have closed loop monitoring or controls. =E2=80=9CWhen we ta=
lk to people about what we=E2=80=99re building,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9C=
the heavy-hitter question is: will you be able to get telemetry data faster=
