Why Texas?=C2=A0
Everything is bigger in Texas, and everything I just wrote is supercharged =
in Texas.=C2=A0
In that Week 3 Update, Zach wrote that Base would not start by focusing on =
Texas because, as an unregulated market, prices in Texas are volatile. He a=
lso wrote that Base would not build an REP, because the need to hedge would=
 make the business more capital intensive and riskier.=C2=A0
But one of Base=E2=80=99s principles, picked up from its team=E2=80=99s tim=
e at SpaceX and Tesla, is =E2=80=9CQuestion Assumptions.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Like: the need to hedge power price risk would make the business more capit=
al intensive and riskier. At some point, the team realized that batteries w=
ere the hedge, and that because of that, they=E2=80=99d have a built-in adv=
antage over the competition.=C2=A0
Then: if you=E2=80=99re an REP with batteries, then price volatility can be=
 a very good thing.=C2=A0
And: if you=E2=80=99re looking for volatility, there=E2=80=99s no better pl=
ace to look than Texas.=C2=A0
When it comes to power, Texas is an island. Its grid, managed by ERCOT (Ele=
ctric Reliability Council of Texas) is mostly isolated from the rest of the=
 United States=E2=80=99 power grids.=C2=A0
While California and New York also have their own Independent System Operat=
ors, Texas is the only state whose grid isn=E2=80=99t interconnected with o=
ther state=E2=80=99s grids.=C2=A0
From a regulatory standpoint, that means that Texas is the only grid not fe=
derally regulated by FERC (Federal Energy Regulatory Commission). The Publi=
c Utility Commission of Texas (PUC) regulates ERCOT, particularly as it con=
cerns electricity rates.=C2=A0
From a reliability standpoint, it means that Texan generators are responsib=
le for producing the power that Texan consumers consume.=C2=A0
Interconnections =E2=80=93 the physical and operational links between diffe=
rent power systems that allow them to transfer electricity among each other=
 =E2=80=93 allow other states to rely on each other to balance their grids.=
 They can balance supply and demand across a wider range of generation capa=
bilities, local weather conditions, and demand profiles. Texas is all on it=
s own.=C2=A0
A grid is a tricky thing to manage all by yourself, made more tricky in rec=
ent years by the growing share of renewables in Texas=E2=80=99 generation m=
ix. Texas is blessed by nature. It sits at the intersection of America=E2=
=80=99s Sun Belt and its Wind Belt, and as a result, it is the country=E2=
=80=99s largest wind power producer and its second largest solar producer.=
=C2=A0
It may surprise you that Texas is so big on renewables, until you realize t=
hat Texas is the most free market of all of the grids. It=E2=80=99s an ener=
gy-only market in which power plants are paid only for the energy they prod=
uce, and unlike in regulated markets, in which utilities can choose the sou=
rce of power they provide to customers based on other factors like reliabil=
ity, Texan generators compete in wholesale markets based on price. When the=
y=E2=80=99re on, solar and wind have a cheaper marginal price than other po=
wer sources, so they win, at the expense of reliability.=C2=A0
The market makes up for this through scarcity pricing mechanisms: ERCOT int=
roduces congestion pricing =E2=80=93 kind of like Uber=E2=80=99s surge pric=
ing =E2=80=93 to incentivize more capacity to come online when it=E2=80=99s=
 needed. It=E2=80=99s the only grid without a capacity market, in which gen=
erators are paid simply for being available to produce if needed, opting to=
 ensure reliability through market signals alone.=C2=A0
As a result, the transition to renewables and electrified everything has be=
en particularly bumpy in Texas, where electricity is cheaper when the getti=
ng=E2=80=99s good but less reliable when it isn=E2=80=99t. Plus, Texas has =
more extreme weather =E2=80=93 very hot and very cold =E2=80=93 than its re=
newable-heavy counterparts like California. As a result, last year, Texans =
experienced 20 hours without electricity, up 6x from three hours in 2013.=
=C2=A0
The point of a free market, though, is that while it can be messier in the =
short-run than a centrally-planned one, it leaves room for market-based sol=
utions that can be better in the long-run. Base thinks it can be part of th=
at solution, and that Texas is the ideal place for it to start.
First, because Texans are experiencing more frequent and longer outages, th=
e battery value prop resonates with them in a way that=E2=80=99s hard to un=
derstand if you live in a state with a more stable grid. A more acute need =
paired with an economical solution should help it grow its customer base as=
 quickly as its installation pace will allow.=C2=A0
Second, once those batteries are in place, they can be more profitable in T=
exas than they would be in other states. On Sunday morning, I pulled up Gri=
dStatus.io [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d9acdc4-fcc1-4098-b080-3bbc6997=
2f7d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (=
which is worth checking out for a feel for how all of this works), and this=
 is what I saw:=C2=A0=C2=A0
While each of the other ISOs real-time prices pretty closely tracked day-ah=
ead prices (predictions made the day ahead, which are purchasable), ERCOT r=
eal-time prices ($92/MWh) had spiked far above day-ahead prices ($23/MWh). =
If Base charged its batteries overnight at $15/MWh real-time prices, it cou=
ld have made $77 for every MWh it discharged back to the grid. And that=E2=
=80=99s actually a low spread. There are some days in the summer when you c=
an charge for $0 and discharge for $5,000/MWh.=C2=A0
It doesn=E2=80=99t take too many days like that to pay back an ~$8,000 20MW=
h battery.=C2=A0
Base can build a big business in Texas alone, but it plans to prove the mod=
el in Texas, then move on to other deregulated markets as more renewables a=
nd electrification destabilize their grids, too.=C2=A0
California is an interesting next target for a battery company: because so =
much solar is produced in the middle of the day, Base could be paid to char=
ge, and then discharge when prices are above zero. After deregulated market=
s, it can partner with utilities in regulated markets as they too shift to =
more renewables, and their customers electrify more of their energy consump=
tion.=C2=A0
By cutting its teeth in Texas, Base believes it can become one of the most =
sophisticated Virtual Power Plant (VPP) operators in the market. Then, it c=
an compete with companies like Tesla, Sunrun, and Sunnova in regulated mark=
ets, where they currently partner with existing utilities to run VPPs. Base=
 thinks that by flipping the model - from selling hardware to selling power=
 =E2=80=93 it can win against the companies who have failed to aggregate mu=
ch demand due to lack of customers willing to pay.=C2=A0
Or, Base hopes, by showing that deregulated energy markets can work really =
well in Texas, it can convince other states to adopt regulatory frameworks =
more similar to the Lone Star State=E2=80=99s. To be fair, Texas=E2=80=99 d=
eregulated energy-only market has been a mixed bag. In 2021, Winter Storm U=
ri left millions of Texans without power for days and left the whole market=
 shook.=C2=A0
But if Base is right, and it can prove it in Texas, it might show that rene=
wables, free markets, and batteries offer a combination of low-prices and r=
eliability that regulated systems can=E2=80=99t match.=C2=A0
As former PUC Commissioner Will McAdams said on the Energy Capital Podcast =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/9297ad72-0e4c-4f54-b4ed-8b165d8e0311?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
We've doubled our battery capacity. We will double it again very soon. And =
batteries are right at home in what's going on right now. It has been an in=
valuable resource and will be a critical resource managing through the seas=
ons that we're soon to see with the amount of load growth patterns that we =
have today. And so every energy company in the world is either looking at T=
exas or has invested capital in Texas to some degree.
But that=E2=80=99s a long way away. For now, Texas will keep Base busy for =
a long time. There are 11 million homes in the state, increasingly powered =
by renewable energy, with a quarter of a million electric vehicles to plug =
in at the end of each day, growing to half a million with haste. If Base ca=
n fix Texas=E2=80=99 grid, it can fix =E2=80=98em all. And in the process, =
it can build up one of the largest and most profitable battery storage port=
folios in the country.=C2=A0
The Base Business Model=C2=A0
We just covered a lot of complexity to arrive back at a business model that=
=E2=80=99s really quite simple:=C2=A0
building a large portfolio of connected batteries with short paybacks and h=
igh cash on cash returns.=C2=A0
Building storage portfolios is a good business no matter how you slice it, =
so good that Casey Handmer used an exclamation point when he wrote [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/9cf0c5ed-2e41-4abb-8997-b4b72b355979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CIndeed, wh=
ile new solar farms take 5-20 years to pay for themselves, battery plants a=
re so lucrative they=E2=80=99re often profitable by year two =E2=80=93 whic=
h is unheard of in the energy infrastructure space!=E2=80=9D
Broad Reach, which was founded in 2019, was acquired for $1 billion in equi=
ty value [ https://substack.com/redirect/0667fb9e-1012-44aa-8ae8-e9fac88a97=
50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in =
2023, at just four years old, and with only 350 MW of storage in operation =
(with another 880 MW under construction). Now that batteries are getting ch=
eaper, renewables are getting more plentiful, and demand for electricity is=
 picking up, building a profitable portfolio of batteries is easier than it=
=E2=80=99s ever been.=C2=A0
But to build the most profitable portfolio, and one that alleviates the gri=
d=E2=80=99s challenges, Base believes that you need to do a whole lot of ha=
rd things, at once, in such a way that the whole system works in a way that=
 no competitor can match.=C2=A0
You need to manufacture batteries, and design a whole Deployment Factory, o=
ptimized to lower the cost of the whole installation at scale.=C2=A0
You need to offer the batteries as part of a larger REP offering, and offer=
 them at install cost (taking on the cost of the battery yourself) in order=
 to increase adoption.=C2=A0
You need to turn that adoption into a distributed network of batteries that=
 produces demand signals in real-time, and can charge and dispatch on-deman=
d in order to profitably trade power and offer ancillary services to the gr=
id.=C2=A0
And you need to start in Texas, the most isolated and volatile grid in Amer=
ica, in order to create, and capture, the most value.=C2=A0
To make it more clear, let=E2=80=99s look at that ERCOT summer 2023 chart a=
gain.=C2=A0
In a purely financial market, an arbitrage like that would get traded away =
within minutes, maybe seconds.=C2=A0
But batteries aren=E2=80=99t a purely financial market. Accessing the arbit=
rage requires a lot of hard engineering, manufacturing, distribution, sales=
, and software.=C2=A0
If you can pull all of that off, you have the arbitrage practically to your=
self as long as you can keep competitors at bay.
To that end, and I will bang this drum until my face turns blue, digging a =
moat is key [ https://substack.com/redirect/65c26b61-dd17-40cf-a37e-09a9f4a=
42807?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
=E2=80=9CThe moat,=E2=80=9D Zach told me, =E2=80=9Cis =E2=80=98hard.=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=9D
Each of the high-level things that Base does has a thousand sub-steps, and =
a small team of talented people within the company tasked with making sure =
they=E2=80=99re executed in lockstep. With each coherent action they pull o=
ff, the moat against would-be competitors deepens.=C2=A0
Manufacturing its own batteries means it won=E2=80=99t need to pay a margin=
 to battery companies like the battery farms do. Using those batteries to o=
ffer better reliability and cheaper prices than other REPs means it should =
be able to acquire customers more cheaply, and retain them longer. Adding m=
ore batteries to the grid gives Base more data in more locations than anyon=
e in Texas, and a greater ability to profit on that data. Continuing to hir=
e world-class engineering talent in an industry that traditionally hasn=E2=
=80=99t means that they can keep doing all of those things better and faste=
r than a competitor can.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the plan, at least.=C2=A0
Today, Base is officially online in Texas, serving a handful of homes with =
third-party batteries and REP service, powered by Base=E2=80=99s software. =
It=E2=80=99s aiming to ramp up to dozens installs by the end of Q2. In Q4, =
it will roll out v1 of its own Base-manufactured batteries, which will spee=
d up installation and improve Base=E2=80=99s responsiveness to the grid=E2=
=80=99s needs. As it installs, it=E2=80=99s learning and adjusting. HOA=E2=
=80=99s are proving to be trickier than expected, but they=E2=80=99re figur=
ing it out.=C2=A0
For now, Base is financing batteries off of its own balance sheet. In the m=
onths ahead, it needs to grow the portfolio and prove out the economics of =
its batteries so that it can secure asset-backed loans to fuel its growth. =
Building a portfolio that appeals to lenders means that Base can unlock a l=
ower cost of capital, which means more batteries and more profits, and ulti=
mately even lower costs of capital. The moat widens.=C2=A0
Combine the balance sheet of a PE-backed storage portfolio with the enginee=
ring and operational chops of a SpaceX in a trillion-dollar market, and you=
=E2=80=99re in business.=C2=A0
That said, Base is trying to build a power company on hard mode, and there =
are a lot of challenges =E2=80=93 real and surmountable =E2=80=93 ahead. Le=
t=E2=80=99s go through them.=C2=A0
The Arguments Against Base
The simplest reason that Base might fail is the same as its moat if it succ=
eeds: it=E2=80=99s hard.=C2=A0
That should be painfully obvious at this point. Manufacturing batteries is =
hard. Installing them is hard. Acquiring customers is hard. Convincing them=
 to pay for a big battery on the side of their house is hard. Power trading=
 is hard. Distributed software is hard. Financing a portfolio of individual=
 batteries with no offtake agreements is hard. Each thing that Base has to =
do individually is hard, and the model depends on all of them working toget=
her. That=E2=80=99s why hiring has been the highest priority, but even with=
 the best people, getting all of this right will be hard. That=E2=80=99s ob=
vious.=C2=A0
But there are more nuanced arguments for why Base might not work, or might =
not be needed, and I asked the team about them. They range from dumb to sma=
rt.=C2=A0
The dumb argument is that we won=E2=80=99t need batteries if we just add a =
bunch of nuclear, which we should. There are a few reasons this one doesn=
=E2=80=99t hold up.=C2=A0
The first is that adding new nuclear capacity is really hard. With Vogtle 4=
 online, there are no new large-scale nuclear projects in the pipeline. We =
should do everything we can to change that =E2=80=93 and I=E2=80=99m partic=
ularly excited about hyperscalers adding nuclear to power AI datacenters =
=E2=80=93 but we can=E2=80=99t rely on nuclear as our only hope.=C2=A0
More importantly, in a way that I didn=E2=80=99t fully appreciate before ta=
lking to the Base team, nuclear and batteries are complementary. Nuclear is=
 a generation technology, and batteries are a distribution technology, like=
 poles and wires. More and cheaper batteries make nuclear more useful by ma=
king it more dispatchable.=C2=A0
The =E2=80=9Cin between smart and dumb=E2=80=9D argument is that if your co=
re business is arbitrage, you kill your business by providing stability. Th=
ere are a few answers to this one, too.=C2=A0
The first is that the problem is so large that if Base and other battery co=
mpanies fix it, they will have built enormous businesses. Plus, maintaining=
 stability will rely on those batteries continuing to operate, and lower vo=
latility will mean less opportunity for new entrants.=C2=A0
The second is that electricity is a commodity, and commodities don=E2=80=99=
t flatline. Generation and demand will continue to be unpredictable. The su=
n will always go down at night, and people will continue to plug things in =
and turn them on whenever they need.=C2=A0
Another in between argument is that people are buying EVs anyway, and those=
 EVs have big batteries, so shouldn=E2=80=99t we just use those?=C2=A0
This one makes sense on the surface. The car battery is a resource that cus=
tomers have already paid for, and that just sits there overnight. But the s=
imple counter is that they=E2=80=99re cars, and they=E2=80=99re designed to=
 be on the road. It only takes one or two times when someone needs to drive=
 when the battery is at 20% for them to realize it=E2=80=99s not worth it.=
=C2=A0
More subtly, car battery warranties are based on the cycle life. Charging a=
nd discharging too often might mess up the battery and knock it out of warr=
anty. There=E2=80=99s a reason that even though Tesla has more car batterie=
s in garages than any company in America, they sell a separate home battery=
 product.=C2=A0
The smart argument is that grid infrastructure today isn=E2=80=99t built fo=
r big batteries charging and discharging. They were built for power plants =
to send electricity one-way over transmission and distribution lines, and f=
or homes to consume the electricity they receive when they receive it.=C2=
=A0
At the neighborhood level, the distribution transformer won=E2=80=99t be ab=
le to support the batteries, so you need to pay ~$2,000 to upgrade the tran=
sformer. Financially and technically, it=E2=80=99s an easy fix once you hav=
e a few customers in a neighborhood.=C2=A0
The bigger challenge is that upgrading the grid, even if you=E2=80=99re not=
 installing new lines, is hard because it requires navigating all of the hu=
man complexities that you can=E2=80=99t solve with technology.=C2=A0
The grid still doesn=E2=80=99t have real-time telemetry, for example, even =
though the technology exists, because people haven=E2=80=99t agreed on gett=
ing it done. Is there funding? Where does the money come from? That particu=
lar bottleneck is an advantage for Base =E2=80=93 they can get data that no=
 one else can =E2=80=93 but the dynamics behind that bottleneck might slow =
it down in other places.=C2=A0
Getting transmission to work with batteries will require good ol=E2=80=99 f=
ashioned facetime. =E2=80=9CWe need to work with the grid operators, spend =
a lot of time with them, and partner with them,=E2=80=9D Zach told me. =E2=
=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re coming in at a good time. They=E2=80=99re actively work=
ing to find solutions and they understand that technology can help.=E2=80=
=9D
=E2=80=9CIt will be hard, but it=E2=80=99s doable.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
A bet on Base is a bet that it can pull off a series of hard but doable cha=
llenges =E2=80=93 technical, operational, financial, and human.=C2=A0
We should be rooting for them. Because the world is a better place if Base =
succeeds.=C2=A0
What if Base Succeeds?=C2=A0
There are a couple things I believe, which you=E2=80=99ll know if you=E2=80=
=99ve been reading Not Boring for a while.
The first is that energy is upstream of progress. More clean energy is good=
, full stop.
The second is that startups can take on incumbents to reshape huge, stagnan=
t industries.=C2=A0
If Base succeeds, it will help unlock energy abundance and prove that start=
ups can take on industries as large and seemingly unshakeable as power and =
win.
At this point in the essay, the energy abundance unlock should be clear. By=
 helping to stabilize the grid in the face of more volatile demand and supp=
ly, Base can accelerate the addition of renewable and nuclear generation an=
d the electrification of everything.=C2=A0
Just last week, Goldman put out a report projecting data center electricity=
 demand to at a 15% CAGR from now through 2030, and that by 2030, data cent=
ers make up 8% of total US power demand, up from 3% now. They=E2=80=99ll re=
quire 47 GW of additional generation capacity, which Goldman projects will =
be met with 60% natural gas and 40% renewables.=C2=A0
AI power demand has been the biggest upside surprise, and there may be more=
 coming. Manufacturing robots at scale will take time, but what happens whe=
n a growing portion of the labor market is powered with electrons instead o=
f food? What happens if, despite Ron DeSantis=E2=80=99 best efforts, we can=
 grow our food from cells instead of factory farmed animals?=C2=A0
In all of these cases and more, cheap, reliable electricity is a key input =
to an abundant future.=C2=A0
Less obviously, if Base succeeds in competing with power utilities, it will=
 prove that startups now have the tools to take on the most established inc=
umbents to solve our biggest challenges.=C2=A0
Power utilities are the largest state-sanctioned monopolies we have in Amer=
ica. The top 10 utilities and utility owners have combined market caps of o=
ver $600 billion.=C2=A0
Many of these companies are over 100 years old, the result of decades of me=
rgers and acquisitions. They=E2=80=99re among the largest and least innovat=
ive companies in the world. We shouldn=E2=80=99t just accept that they=E2=
=80=99re the best we can do.=C2=A0
The utilities seem untouchable, even though if you were starting fresh, you=
 would never build a utility with the generation portfolio that they have. =
You wouldn=E2=80=99t build coal plants =E2=80=93 utilities are spending mil=
lions to decommission them =E2=80=93 you might build some natural gas plant=
s, and you=E2=80=99d build a whole lot more solar and nuclear, like they=E2=
=80=99re all scrambling to do now.=C2=A0
The mega-bull case for Base is that it can build a modern utility by starti=
ng on the demand side instead of the supply side. Fix the grid=E2=80=99s bi=
g bottleneck, build a power company that customers actually love, hack away=
 on all of the challenges that pop up with tech, and eventually, vertically=
 integrate into supply.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re going to need a lot more clean energy, and someone is going t=
o have to build it. With enough customers and enough batteries, Base will k=
now who needs that power, when and where. It can build solar farms and nucl=
ear plants, sell direct to its own customers, and cut out the middleman, lo=
wering prices. It can produce energy, store it, and discharge it as needed.=
 The supply and demand books are hedges for each other.=C2=A0
Like a bank that lends customer deposits, Base would have a lower cost of c=
apital on supply by owning demand.=C2=A0
If they pull it off, that will be a hard-earned advantage and the basis for=
 a generational company.=C2=A0
Base is a prime Techno-Industrial [ https://substack.com/redirect/32b5d92c-=
ce04-4285-ace8-570a71e77053?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. It plans to capture a big chunk of a large incumbent=
-dominated topline and pair it with software-like margins. What does a PG&E=
 or Southern Company with high free cash flow margins look like?=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
But all of that is in the future. The strategy makes sense, the team is str=
ong, and the mission is big. For now, it=E2=80=99s about executing, learnin=
g, and iterating.=C2=A0
Do that enough, and you just might end up building The Modern Power Company=
 of the Electric Era, one that makes the world an objectively better place.
Thanks to Zach, Justin, Cole and Jared for your input, for all the people w=
ho=E2=80=99ve written excellent stuff on the grid and batteries, and to Gau=
rav for introducing us.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! If you enjoyed and learned a little bit, spre=
ad the good word.=20
We=E2=80=99ll catch you on Friday for our Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

