=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>This is an incredible chart. It shows that while the cost t=
o </span><em>produce</em><span> electricity has fallen 33% from 6.8 cents p=
er kilowatt hour (kWh) to 4.6 cents/kWh over the past decade, electricity i=
s no cheaper than it was in 2010. That&#8217;s because the cost to </span><=
em>deliver </em><span>electricity has </span><em>increased</em><span> by 65=
%, from 2.6 cents/kWh to 4.3 cents/kWh.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><=
span>Energy is fundamentally critical and unbelievably complex. Last year, =
Julia DeWahl and I spent a whole </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/red=
irect/1a841e42-4609-44ca-9373-509fb0676407?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); te=
xt-decoration: underline;">10-episode season</a><span> digging into how Ame=
rica can start producing nuclear energy again. But nuclear is just one gene=
ration technology, and generation (or </span><strong>production</strong><sp=
an>) is just one of the three legs of the electricity stool alongside </spa=
n><strong>delivery</strong><span> and </span><strong>consumption</strong><s=
pan>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">For the energy transition to succee=
d, and for the world to consume multiples more energy than we do today, all=
 three legs need to improve.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">On the production s=
ide, we need more and cheaper nuclear, solar, wind, geothermal, synthetic f=
uels, and other carbon-free sources of energy.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">O=
n the consumption side, we need to electrify everything we can economically=
 electrify &#8211; from cars to heat pumps to appliances.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">The good news is: both are happening!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
Solar is getting unbelievably cheap, electric vehicle (EV) penetration cont=
inues to rise, and scores of incredibly smart people are working to produce=
 electricity more cheaply and consume that cheap electricity in more ways.&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The bad news is: both of those things actually m=
ake the delivery problem worse!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Delivery involve=
s moving electrons from where they&#8217;re produced to where they&#8217;re=
 consumed, like from a coal plant or solar farm to a home or business. Ther=
e&#8217;s transmission &#8211; moving electrons over long distances from po=
wer plants to substations using high-voltage lines &#8211; and distribution=
 &#8211; moving electrons from the substation to homes and businesses over =
the regular low-voltage power lines you&#8217;re used to seeing.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">This whole electricity delivery system is known as &#8220;=
the grid.&#8221; And the grid is a bit of a mess.&#160;</p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><span>It&#8217;s buckling due to four factors Construction Physics&#8217;=
 Brian Potter </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4cde3685-1904=
-4d69-b741-f90c7936fb27?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: unde=
rline;">describes</a><span> as, &#8220;increasing use of variable sources o=
f electricity, decreasing grid reliability, increasing delay in building el=
ectrical infrastructure, and increasing demand for electricity.&#8221;</spa=
n></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The bookend threats &#8211; increasing use of=
 variable sources of electricity and increasing demand for electricity &#82=
11; present a particularly paradoxical problem. </span><strong>The more pro=
gress we make in wind, solar, EVs, and electric stoves, the more unstable t=
he grid gets.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The power supply is=
 increasingly </span><strong>variable</strong><span> and unreliable. The de=
mand for power is growing and increasingly </span><strong>volatile</strong>=
<span>. Just as everyone gets home, plugs in their Tesla, and turns on all =
of their shiny electric stuff, the sun sets!&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">With more demand for electricity, delivery gets more expensive, b=
ecause transmission lines need to be sized for peak load. One solution is j=
ust to add more transmission capacity, but fixing the grid itself by modern=
izing or adding transmission is, like any big project in America, getting h=
arder, slower, and more expensive to do.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>T=
his is </span><em>the</em><span> bottleneck standing between us and our cle=
an, abundant energy future, and it&#8217;s the piece of the energy puzzle t=
hat has attracted the least entrepreneurial attention.&#160;</span></p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">So it&#8217;s the challenge that Base Power Company plans to =
solve.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Base is building &#8220;</span><str=
ong>the Modern Power Company of the Electric Era</strong><span>.&#8221;&#16=
0;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>It&#8217;s starting by deploying conne=
cted </span><strong>batteries</strong><span> across the grid in places wher=
e interconnect already exists and where the demand happens: in peoples&#821=
7; homes, beginning with Texas.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, =
55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Batteries=
