 </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9cf0c5ed-2e41-4abb-8997-b4=
b72b355979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">write=
s</a><span>, &#8220;Transmission moves power through space (technically nul=
l space, at the speed of light).&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>T=
his is both a miracle and a curse. a16z&#8217;s Ryan McEntush </span><a hre=
f=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/0c372d86-ee79-466f-a7ad-92ab218d441d?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">explains this dou=
ble-edged sword</a><span>: &#8220;At all times,</span><strong> electricity =
generated must match electricity demand</strong><span>, or &#8216;load&#821=
7;; this is what people mean when they say &#8216;balance the grid.&#8217;&=
#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Making matters more challeng=
ing, the grid has to be sized for </span><strong>peak load</strong><span>: =
for that really hot day every decade when everyone turns their AC all the w=
ay up all at once. There needs to be enough generation capacity to produce =
the load and enough transmission capacity to move it, even if it&#8217;s ve=
ry infrequently used.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In an intervi=
ew for Age of Miracles, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/67d=
920da-5242-4bdf-a570-f16826fe2504?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decora=
tion: underline;">Meredith Angwin</a><span>, the &#8220;Grandmother of the =
Grid,&#8221; told us that utilities have to pay certain generation faciliti=
es to just not shut down, even if they&#8217;re not producing power, just i=
n case they&#8217;re needed. These &#8220;capacity payments&#8221; make eve=
ryone&#8217;s electric bill higher. They&#8217;re an inelegant financial ba=
nd-aid for a problem that can now be solved with technology.&#160;</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">Balancing the grid has always been a challenge, one oft=
en solved by picking up the phone and frantically calling generation facili=
ties to turn production on or off ASAP, or by dumping perfectly good electr=
icity with nowhere to go. Occasionally, when things go really wrong, there =
are blackouts, which cause everything from inconvenience to economic interr=
uption to death.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But largely, for most of its li=
fe, the grid worked. Baseload power plants run consistently to meet the con=
sistent demand for electricity, and more expensive peaker plants are dispat=
ched as needed to meet higher periods of demand. Supply was dispatchable as=
-needed, and demand, while weather-dependent, was predictable.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Back in college, I interned on an energy trading desk, and e=
very morning, the first thing I did was check the weather: if it was going =
to be really hot, prices would spike as more expensive peaker plants came o=
nline. But if I, as a dumb intern, knew that, it was a very predictable and=
 largely non-threatening spike.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">With the rise of=
 renewables and the electrification of everything, that&#8217;s changed. &#=
8220;For most of its history, electric power generation worked like any oth=
er machine - it was turned on when it was needed, and turned off when it wa=
sn&#8217;t,&#8221; Brian Potter wrote, &#8220;But the predictability of pow=
er generation is slowly going out the window.&#8221;</p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I=
nstead of (largely) predictable supply serving (largely) predictable demand=
, we increasingly have volatile supply meeting volatile (and growing) deman=
d.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-s=
