16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">To fix the grid, just add bat=
teries.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Smoothing electricity supply and d=
emand over time is what batteries were born to do. In the bluntly titled </=
span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9cf0c5ed-2e41-4abb-8997-b=
4b72b355979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Grid=
 Storage: Why Batteries Will Win</a></em><span>, Casey Handmer wrote:&#160;=
</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20p=
x 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Here&#8217=
;s the key insight. Batteries and transmission are in direct competition. B=
oth enable electricity arbitrage &#8211; the profitable repricing of a reso=
urce by matching different levels of supply and demand. Transmission moves =
power through space (technically null space, at the speed of light) and </s=
pan><strong>batteries move power through time</strong><span>.</span></em></=
p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">What follows from that key insight is a th=
orough and data-driven demolition of the idea that adding more grid is the =
right way to fix the grid. A few highlights:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"=
border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Adding 12 hours of storage to the entire U=
S grid would not happen overnight, but on current trends would cost around =
$500b and pay for itself within a few years. This is a shorter timescale th=
an the required manufacturing ramp, meaning it could be entirely privately =
funded. By contrast, upgrading the US transmission grid could </span><stron=
g><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/3dfddd49-1d84-40c7-bf45-10fc1453=
7813?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" re=
l style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">cost $7t ov=
er 20 years</a></strong><span>.</span></em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left=
: 20px;"><em><span>In all cases, we see </span><strong>a grid without stora=
ge is useless</strong><span>&#8230; Conversely, we see relatively small qua=
ntities of overall storage dramatically decrease the amount of generation o=
verbuild needed. Over a wide range of wind/solar mix and battery installati=
on, we can hit 99.99% reliability (significantly better than the pre-renewa=
ble grid) with &lt; 10x nameplate overbuild. This is how the grid will look=
 in the future.</span></em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><st=
rong>Adding marginal batteries until demand saturates will generate enormou=
s profit and value growth. Adding additional grid is just stranding assets.=
</strong></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Casey calls his view &#822=
0;unconventional, even controversial,&#8221; and arguably his &#8220;spicie=
st hot take on the future of energy,&#8221; but the more I&#8217;ve dug in,=
 the more I agree with him.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Batteries aren&#8217=
;t a generation technology &#8211; we can&#8217;t produce more energy with =
batteries &#8211; but they supercharge other forms of clean generation.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">As we&#8217;ve discussed, batteries are a great com=
plement to variable generation sources like solar and wind. Solar and wind =
produce power whenever the sun shines and the wind blows, but people&#8217;=
s energy consumption doesn&#8217;t match the weather&#8217;s whims. Batteri=
es can store power generated whenever it&#8217;s generated, and dispatch it=
 whenever it&#8217;s needed.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>But batteries=
 are also a great complement to nuclear power. As Base wrote in a recent me=
mo, &#8220;Nuclear has high upfront costs but very low operating costs. Loa=
d side storage helps match the consistent output of nuclear to variable loa=
d and increases the economic value of energy generated from nuclear.&#8221;=
 </span><strong>Batteries make nuclear dispatchable</strong><span>.</span><=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In fact, they point out, </span><strong>batterie=
s are a great complement to any high capex, low opex source of energy.</str=
ong><span> If a plant is expensive to build but produces cheap energy there=
after, batteries can soak up all of the cheap output to be dispatched when =
demand calls. That allows power generation owners to amortize their capex o=
ver more demand, or to pay back their capex more quickly. Batteries make re=
newable energy &#8211; definitionally low opex &#8211; more competitive wit=
h fossil fuel plants, which are less expensive to build but must consistent=
ly feed fuel into the system.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Batteries a=
re also great for the grid.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The grid is designed=
 to carry the peak load customers are expected to demand. If demand gets sp=
ikier, grid operators need to add more transmission capacity to meet peak l=
oads, even if most of that capacity sits unused most of the time.&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Load factor</strong><span> is the ratio of averag=
e power demand to peak power demand over a given period. A low load factor =
means wasted resources. As an example, Texas&#8217; grid is sized for 85 GW=
 based on last summer&#8217;s peak. Currently, it&#8217;s </span><a href=3D=
"https://substack.com/redirect/159e4332-e50b-42ed-81fb-42b16a9ea7b4?j=3DeyJ=
