font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>And the mark=
et is large. Single-family homes account for roughly 20% of US power demand=
, or about $200 billion in annual electricity spend. It&#8217;s not just a =
large market in aggregate, but one of many consumer&#8217;s biggest spendin=
g categories. In 2021, the average American household spent </span><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/8cd86ee1-6dc3-4d8a-b46a-438bd5cb1757?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">$121/month on elec=
tricity</a><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Base plans to compete with t=
his fragmented, low-NPS mass of REPs by offering a modern consumer experien=
ce, backed by a battery.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">On the experience side,=
 Base is probably the only REP with former Apple, Tesla, and Ramp software =
engineers on staff. By doing table-stakes things like Apple/Google/CashApp =
payments, gamification of power usage, and real-time tracking and visualiza=
tion, it can offer a better product experience than competitors can.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The battery, though, is the real differentiator.&#160;=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Obviously, with a battery, customers get more reliabl=
e power. The Base battery will offer hours or days of backup, depending on =
usage. Base customers won&#8217;t have to worry about power outages, becaus=
e when the power goes down on the grid, the battery will just take over. (S=
eeing your neighbor&#8217;s power on while yours is off during an outage is=
 great word of mouth marketing, too).&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Less=
 obviously, but as importantly</span><strong>, the battery means that Base =
can offer customers a lower price on their electricity. </strong><span>The =
reason is counterintuitive.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, =
55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Selling elect=
ricity in a deregulated market is a low-margin, high-risk business. It&#821=
7;s low margin because it&#8217;s competitive, and REPs have to buy from ge=
nerators and sell to price-sensitive consumers. It&#8217;s high risk becaus=
e prices can fluctuate wildly. For most REPs, that makes selling electricit=
y even lower margin, because they need to hedge their risk with financial i=
nstruments for which they pay a premium.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>&=
#8220;The hedge is a financial battery,&#8221; as Jared described it. </spa=
n><strong>&#8220;The battery is a technical hedge.&#8221;</strong><span>&#1=
60;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Since Base can hedge with technology instea=
d of options, it can pass the savings it would have otherwise spent on prem=
iums back to customers.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A better product at a lo=
wer price in a large, highly-fragmented, low NPS market is a good combinati=
on if Base can pull it off.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But Base&#8217;s goa=
l isn&#8217;t to build the world&#8217;s best REP. It wants to build one of=
 the country&#8217;s largest and most profitable battery storage portfolios=
=2E The REP is a channel to get as many=
 batteries as possible distributed acr=
oss the state of Texas, to start, as quickly and cheaply as possible.&#160;=
&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The core business is using those batteries to t=
rade energy and provide ancillary services to the grid.&#160;</p><h3 class=
=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility=
; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibil=
ity; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-system-headlin=
e, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvet=
ica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Sy=
mbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: =
1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Why is distributed better for=
 power trading and ancillary services?&#160;</strong></h3><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>Base plans to make money by soaking up energy when it&#8217;s cheap and di=
scharging it when it&#8217;s expensive. If they do it right, it&#8217;s a w=
in-win: good for the business, and good for the grid.&#160;</p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><span>There are two main ways it can make money this way: </span><str=
ong>power trading</strong><span> and </span><strong>grid ancillary services=
</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Power trading</s=
trong><span> is straightforward: buy low, sell high.&#160;</span></p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">Because Base is an REP, it can buy electricity at off-peak time=
s when prices are low, and sell it back to both customers and the grid when=
 prices are high. Power can be purchased in real-time or day-ahead markets,=
 and owning storage capacity means that Base can purchase in the more stabl=
e day-ahead markets and sell into more volatile real-time markets (or soak =
up more power real-time when prices are unexpectedly low). If Base can cons=
istently charge when prices are low and discharge when they&#8217;re high, =
it can make money.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Now that Base has its first R=
EP customers, it&#8217;s kicked off trading. The image below shows that it =
sold power it had stored &#8211; some to customers, some back to the grid. =
They&#8217;re small numbers, but Base power trading is officially in busine=
ss.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-=
