or absorbing the power needed to support the magnetic and electric fields i=
n transformers, electric motors, and relays), </span><strong>reserves</stro=
ng><span> (standing ready to inject power into the grid in the case of gene=
ration shortfalls), </span><strong>demand response</strong><span> (getting =
paid to lower usage), and </span><strong>ramp support and load following</s=
trong><span> (quickly ramping up or down to match variability in renewable =
energy generation). The grid pays companies for providing these services, e=
ither directly through mechanisms like capacity payments or indirectly thro=
ugh markets.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you&#8217;ve heard of the=
 &#8220;duck curve,&#8221; it&#8217;s the phenomenon where net demand for e=
nergy from the traditional grid is low during the day when solar power is f=
