r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><strong>In a purely financial market, an arbitrage like that would get tr=
aded away within minutes, maybe seconds.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">But batteries aren&#8217;t a purely financial market. Accessing the arbit=
rage requires a lot of hard engineering, manufacturing, distribution, sales=
, and software.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>If you can pull all of t=
hat off, you have the arbitrage practically to yourself as long as you can =
keep competitors at bay.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>To that end, a=
nd I will bang this drum until my face turns blue, </span><a href=3D"https:=
//substack.com/redirect/65c26b61-dd17-40cf-a37e-09a9f4a42807?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">digging a moat is key</a><span=
>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;The moat,&#8221; Zach told me, &#8220=
;is &#8216;hard.&#8217;&#8221;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Each of the high-level =
things that Base does has a thousand sub-steps, and a small team of talente=
d people within the company tasked with making sure they&#8217;re executed =
in lockstep. With each coherent action they pull off, the moat against woul=
d-be competitors deepens.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Manufacturing its own =
batteries means it won&#8217;t need to pay a margin to battery companies li=
ke the battery farms do. Using those batteries to offer better reliability =
and cheaper prices than other REPs means it should be able to acquire custo=
mers more cheaply, and retain them longer. Adding more batteries to the gri=
d gives Base more data in more locations than anyone in Texas, and a greate=
r ability to profit on that data. Continuing to hire world-class engineerin=
g talent in an industry that traditionally hasn&#8217;t means that they can=
 keep doing all of those things better and faster than a competitor can.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s the plan, at least.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Today, Base is officially online in Texas, serving a handful of h=
omes with third-party batteries and REP service, powered by Base&#8217;s so=
ftware. It&#8217;s aiming to ramp up to dozens installs by the end of Q2. I=
n Q4, it will roll out v1 of its own Base-manufactured batteries, which wil=
l speed up installation and improve Base&#8217;s responsiveness to the grid=
&#8217;s needs. As it installs, it&#8217;s learning and adjusting. HOA&#821=
7;s are proving to be trickier than expected, but they&#8217;re figuring it=
 out.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;"><figure style=3D"margi=
