</div><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">For now, Base is financing batteries off of its own=
 balance sheet. In the months ahead, it needs to grow the portfolio and pro=
ve out the economics of its batteries so that it can secure asset-backed lo=
ans to fuel its growth. Building a portfolio that appeals to lenders means =
that Base can unlock a lower cost of capital, which means more batteries an=
d more profits, and ultimately even lower costs of capital. The moat widens=
=2E&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=20=
55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Combine the balance sheet of a PE-backed stora=
ge portfolio with the engineering and operational chops of a SpaceX in a tr=
illion-dollar market, and you&#8217;re in business.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">That said, Base is trying to build a power company on hard mode, and th=
ere are a lot of challenges &#8211; real and surmountable &#8211; ahead. Le=
t&#8217;s go through them.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget"=
 style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: ant=
ialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: a=
ntialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-fa=
mily: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-system-headline, system-ui, -apple-system, B=
linkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple=
 Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; fon=
t-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: rel=
ative;"><strong>The Arguments Against Base</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">T=
he simplest reason that Base might fail is the same as its moat if it succe=
eds: it&#8217;s hard.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That should be painfully o=
bvious at this point. Manufacturing batteries is hard. Installing them is h=
ard. Acquiring customers is hard. Convincing them to pay for a big battery =
on the side of their house is hard. Power trading is hard. Distributed soft=
ware is hard. Financing a portfolio of individual batteries with no offtake=
 agreements is hard. Each thing that Base has to do individually is hard, a=
nd the model depends on all of them working together. That&#8217;s why hiri=
ng has been the highest priority, but even with the best people, getting al=
l of this right will be hard. That&#8217;s obvious.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">But there are more nuanced arguments for why Base might not work, or mi=
ght not be needed, and I asked the team about them. They range from dumb to=
 smart.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The </span><strong>dumb</strong><s=
pan> argument is that we won&#8217;t need batteries if we just add a bunch =
of nuclear, which we should. There are a few reasons this one doesn&#8217;t=
 hold up.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The first is that adding new nu=
clear capacity is really hard. With Vogtle 4 online, there are no new large=
-scale nuclear projects in the pipeline. We should do everything we can to =
change that &#8211; and I&#8217;m particularly excited about hyperscalers a=
dding nuclear to power AI datacenters &#8211; but we can&#8217;t rely on nu=
clear as our only hope.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>More importantly, =
in a way that I didn&#8217;t fully appreciate before talking to the Base te=
am, nuclear and batteries are complementary. Nuclear is a generation techno=
logy, and batteries are a distribution technology, like poles and wires. Mo=
re and cheaper batteries make nuclear </span><em>more </em><span>useful by =
making it more dispatchable.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The </=
span><strong>&#8220;in between smart and dumb&#8221;</strong><span> argumen=
t is that if your core business is arbitrage, you kill your business by pro=
viding stability. There are a few answers to this one, too.&#160;</span></p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">The first is that the problem is so large that if Base a=
nd other battery companies fix it, they will have built enormous businesses=
=2E Plus, maintaining stability will re=
ly on those batteries continuing to op=
erate, and lower volatility will mean less opportunity for new entrants.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The second is that electricity is a commodity, and=
 commodities don&#8217;t flatline. Generation and demand will continue to b=
e unpredictable. The sun will always go down at night, and people will cont=
inue to plug things in and turn them on whenever they need.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>Another </span><strong>in between</strong><span> argument=
 is that people are buying EVs anyway, and those EVs have big batteries, so=
 shouldn&#8217;t we just use those?&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This =
one makes sense on the surface. The car battery is a resource that customer=
s have already paid for, and that just sits there overnight. But the simple=
 counter is that they&#8217;re cars, and they&#8217;re designed to be on th=
e road. It only takes one or two times when someone needs to drive when the=
 battery is at 20% for them to realize it&#8217;s not worth it.&#160;</p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">More subtly, car battery warranties are based on the cycle =
life. Charging and discharging too often might mess up the battery and knoc=
k it out of warranty. There&#8217;s a reason that even though Tesla has mor=
e car batteries in garages than any company in America, they sell a separat=
e home battery product.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The </span><strong=
>smart</strong><span> argument is that grid infrastructure today isn&#8217;=
t built for big batteries charging and discharging. They were built for pow=
er plants to send electricity one-way over transmission and distribution li=
nes, and for homes to consume the electricity they receive when they receiv=
e it.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">At the neighborhood level, the dist=
ribution transformer won&#8217;t be able to support the batteries, so you n=
eed to pay ~$2,000 to upgrade the transformer. Financially and technically,=
 it&#8217;s an easy fix once you have a few customers in a neighborhood.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The bigger challenge is that upgrading the grid, e=
ven if you&#8217;re not installing new lines, is hard because it requires n=
avigating all of the human complexities that you can&#8217;t solve with tec=
hnology.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The grid still doesn&#8217;t have real-=
time telemetry, for example, even though the technology exists, because peo=
ple haven&#8217;t agreed on getting it done. Is there funding? Where does t=
he money come from? That particular bottleneck is an advantage for Base &#8=
211; they can get data that no one else can &#8211; but the dynamics behind=
 that bottleneck might slow it down in other places.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">Getting transmission to work with batteries will require good ol&#8217=
; fashioned facetime. &#8220;We need to work with the grid operators, spend=
 a lot of time with them, and partner with them,&#8221; Zach told me. &#822=
0;We&#8217;re coming in at a good time. They&#8217;re actively working to f=
ind solutions and they understand that technology can help.&#8221;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;It will be hard, but it&#8217;s doable.&#8221;&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">A bet on Base is a bet that it can pull off a series of =
hard but doable challenges &#8211; technical, operational, financial, and h=
uman.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We should be rooting for them. Because the=
 world is a better place if Base succeeds.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-wit=
h-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-fon=
t-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-f=
ont-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(54, =
55, 55); font-family: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-system-headline, system-ui, =
-apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sa=
ns-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-si=
ze: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em =
0; position: relative;"><strong>What if Base Succeeds?&#160;</strong></h3><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">There are a couple things I believe, which you&#8217;ll kn=
ow if you&#8217;ve been reading Not Boring for a while.</p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">The first is that energy is upstream of progress. More clean energy is go=
od, full stop.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The second is that startups can take on=
 incumbents to reshape huge, stagnant industries.&#160;</p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><strong>If Base succeeds, it will help unlock energy abundance and prove =
that startups can take on industries as large and seemingly unshakeable as =
power and win.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">At this point in the essay, th=
e energy abundance unlock should be clear. By helping to stabilize the grid=
 in the face of more volatile demand and supply, Base can accelerate the ad=
dition of renewable and nuclear generation and the electrification of every=
thing.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Just last week, Goldman put out a report =
projecting data center electricity demand to at a 15% CAGR from now through=
 2030, and that by 2030, data centers make up 8% of total US power demand, =
up from 3% now. They&#8217;ll require 47 GW of additional generation capaci=
ty, which Goldman projects will be met with 60% natural gas and 40% renewab=
les.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">AI power demand has been the biggest upside=
 surprise, and there may be more coming. Manufacturing robots at scale will=
 take time, but what happens when a growing portion of the labor market is =
powered with electrons instead of food? What happens if, despite Ron DeSant=
is&#8217; best efforts, we can grow our food from cells instead of factory =
farmed animals?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In all of these cases and more, =
cheap, reliable electricity is a key input to an abundant future.&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;">Less obviously, if Base succeeds in competing with power =
utilities, it will prove that startups now have the tools to take on the mo=
st established incumbents to solve our biggest challenges.&#160;</p><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">Power utilities are the largest state-sanctioned monopolies we h=
ave in America. The top 10 utilities and utility owners have combined marke=
t caps of over $600 billion.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-contain=
